<section id="fs-id1635254" class="free-response">
<title>Free Response</title><exercise id="fs-id1421074">
<problem id="fs-id2763308"><para id="fs-id1462948">Describe the similarities and differences between glycogen and starch.</para></problem>
<solution id="fs-id2854177"><label/>
<para id="fs-id2491136">Glycogen and starch are polysaccharides. They are the storage form of glucose. Glycogen is stored in animals in the liver and in muscle cells, whereas starch is stored in the roots, seeds, and leaves of plants. Starch has two different forms, one unbranched (amylose) and one branched (amylopectin), whereas glycogen is a single type of a highly branched molecule.</para></solution>
</exercise>
<exercise id="fs-id2164078">
<problem id="fs-id1876261"><para id="fs-id1396854">Why is it impossible for humans to digest food that contains cellulose?</para></problem>
<solution id="fs-id1510995"><label/>
<para id="fs-id2951825">The <emphasis effect="italics">β</emphasis> 1-4 glycosidic linkage in cellulose cannot be broken down by human digestive enzymes. Herbivores such as cows, buffalos, and horses are able to digest grass that is rich in cellulose and use it as a food source because bacteria and protists in their digestive systems, especially in the rumen, secrete the enzyme cellulase. Cellulases can break down cellulose into glucose monomers that can be used as an energy source by the animal.</para></solution>
</exercise>
